@NODE "FreeClass" "intuition.library/FreeClass()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
        @{"FreeClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 518} -- Frees a boopsi class created by @{"MakeClass()" LINK "MakeClass"}. (V36)@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        success = @{"FreeClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 518}( ClassPtr )
        D0                   A0

        @{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91} @{"FreeClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 518}( @{"struct IClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classes.h/File" 36} * );@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
        For class implementors only.

        Tries to free a boopsi class created by @{"MakeClass()" LINK "MakeClass"}.  This
        won't always succeed: classes with outstanding objects or
        with subclasses cannot be freed.  You cannot allow the code
        which implements the class to be unloaded in this case.

        For public classes, this function will *always* remove
        the class (see @{"RemoveClass()" LINK "RemoveClass"} ) making it unavailable, whether
        it succeeds or not.

        If you have a dynamically allocated data for your class (hanging
        off of cl_UserData), try to free the class before you free the
        user data, so you don't get stuck with a half-freed class.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
        ClassPtr - pointer to a class created by @{"MakeClass()" LINK "MakeClass"}.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
        Returns @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98} if the class could not be freed.  Reasons include,
        but will not be limited to, having non-zero cl_ObjectCount or
        cl_SubclassCount.

        Returns @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95} if the class could be freed.

        Calls @{"RemoveClass()" LINK "RemoveClass"} for the class in either case.@{b}

    EXAMPLE@{ub}
        Freeing a private class with dynamically allocated user data:

        freeMyClass( cl )
        @{"struct IClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classes.h/File" 36}   *cl;
        {
            struct MyPerClassData       *mpcd;

            mpcd = (struct MyPerClassData *) cl->cl_UserData;
            if ( @{"FreeClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 518}( cl ) )
            {
                @{"FreeMem" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/exec/FreeMem"}( mpcd, sizeof mpcd );
                return ( @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95} );
            }
            else
            {
                return ( @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98} );
            }
        }@{b}

    BUGS@{ub}@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"MakeClass()" LINK "MakeClass"},
        Document "Basic @{"Object" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 19}-Oriented Programming @{"System" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/dos/SystemTagList"} for @{"Intuition" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 33}"
        and the "boopsi @{"Class" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classes.h/File" 36} Reference" document.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FreeRemember" "intuition.library/FreeRemember()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
        @{"FreeRemember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 279} -- Free memory allocated by calls to @{"AllocRemember()" LINK "AllocRemember"}.@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        @{"FreeRemember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 279}( RememberKey, ReallyForget )
                      A0           D0

        @{"VOID" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 24} @{"FreeRemember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 279}( @{"struct Remember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 1430} **, @{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91} );@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function frees up memory allocated by the @{"AllocRemember()" LINK "AllocRemember"} function.
        It will either free up just the Remember structures, which supply the
        link nodes that tie your allocations together, or it will deallocate
        both the link nodes AND your memory buffers too.

        If you want to deallocate just the Remember structure link nodes,
        you should set the ReallyForget argument to @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98}.  However, if you
        want @{"FreeRemember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 279} to really deallocate all the memory, including
        both the Remember structure link nodes and the buffers you requested
        via earlier calls to @{"AllocRemember()" LINK "AllocRemember"}, then you should set the
        ReallyForget argument to @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95}.

        NOTE WELL: Once you call this function passing it @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98}, the
        linkages between all the memory chunks are lost, and you
        cannot subsequently use @{"FreeRemember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 279}() to free them.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
        RememberKey = the address of a pointer to @{"struct Remember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 1430}.  This
           pointer should either be @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101} or set to some value (possibly
           @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101}) by a call to @{"AllocRemember()" LINK "AllocRemember"}.
        ReallyForget = a @{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91} @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98} or @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95} describing, respectively,
           whether you want to free up only the Remember nodes or
           if you want this procedure to really forget about all of
           the memory, including both the nodes and the memory buffers
           referenced by the nodes.@{b}

    EXAMPLE@{ub}
        @{"struct Remember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 1430} *RememberKey;
        RememberKey = @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101};
        @{"AllocRemember" LINK "AllocRemember"}(&RememberKey, BUFSIZE, @{"MEMF_CHIP" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/memory.h/File" 70});
        @{"FreeRemember" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 279}(&RememberKey, @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95});@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
        None@{b}

    BUGS@{ub}@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"AllocRemember()" LINK "AllocRemember"}, @{"exec.library/FreeMem()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/exec/FreeMem"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FreeScreenBuffer" "intuition.library/FreeScreenBuffer()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
        @{"FreeScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 526} -- Free a ScreenBuffer structure. (V39)@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        @{"FreeScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 526}( Screen, ScreenBuffer )
                          A0      A1

        @{"VOID" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 24} @{"FreeScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 526}( @{"struct Screen" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/screens.h/File" 133} *, @{"struct ScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/screens.h/File" 645} * );@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
        Frees a ScreenBuffer structure you got from @{"AllocScreenBuffer()" LINK "AllocScreenBuffer"},
        and releases associated resources.  You must call @{"FreeScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 526}()
        before you close your screen.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
        Screen: pointer to the screen this ScreenBuffer is associated with.
        ScreenBuffer: pointer to a ScreenBuffer structure obtained from
            @{"AllocScreenBuffer()" LINK "AllocScreenBuffer"}.  It is safe to call this function with
            a @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101} argument.  It will have no effect.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
        None.@{b}

    NOTES@{ub}
        Originally, @{"FreeScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 526}() did not @{"WaitBlit()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/graphics/WaitBlit"} before freeing
        a BitMap.  The intent was that the application should do this.
        However, as this sort of thing is easily forgotten, @{"WaitBlit()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/graphics/WaitBlit"}
        was added in V40.  Application writers should ensure that freeing
        the buffer is safe by calling @{"WaitBlit()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/graphics/WaitBlit"} themselves.

        The @{"SB_SCREEN_BITMAP" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/screens.h/File" 653} flag instructs @{"AllocScreenBuffer()" LINK "AllocScreenBuffer"} to provide
        a ScreenBuffer referring to the screen's actual bitmap.  When
        you are done changing screen buffers, you must @{"FreeScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 526}()
        the currently-installed ScreenBuffer before you close the screen.
        Intuition will recognize when @{"FreeScreenBuffer" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 526}() is called for
        the currently-installed ScreenBuffer, and will know to free the
        supporting structures but not the BitMap.  @{"CloseScreen()" LINK "CloseScreen"} will
        take care of that.@{b}

    BUGS@{ub}@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"AllocScreenBuffer()" LINK "AllocScreenBuffer"}, @{"ChangeScreenBuffer()" LINK "ChangeScreenBuffer"},
        @{"graphics.library/ChangeVPBitMap()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/graphics/ChangeVPBitMap"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FreeScreenDrawInfo" "intuition.library/FreeScreenDrawInfo()"
@{b}

   NAME@{ub}
        @{"FreeScreenDrawInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 506} -- Finish using a DrawInfo structure. (V36)@{b}

   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        @{"FreeScreenDrawInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 506}( Screen, DrInfo )
                            A0      A1

        @{"VOID" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 24} @{"FreeScreenDrawInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 506}( @{"struct Screen" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/screens.h/File" 133} *, @{"struct DrawInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/screens.h/File" 66} * );@{b}

   FUNCTION@{ub}
        Declares that you are finished with the DrawInfo structure
        returned by @{"GetScreenDrawInfo()" LINK "GetScreenDrawInfo"}.@{b}

   INPUTS@{ub}
        Screen - pointer to screen passed to @{"GetScreenDrawInfo()" LINK "GetScreenDrawInfo"}.
        DrInfo - pointer to DrawInfo returned by @{"GetScreenDrawInfo()" LINK "GetScreenDrawInfo"}.
            A @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101} DrawInfo pointer is a valid parameter, signifying
            "do nothing".@{b}

   RESULT@{ub}
        None@{b}

   NOTES@{ub}
        This function, and @{"GetScreenDrawInfo()" LINK "GetScreenDrawInfo"}, don't really do much, but
        they provide an upward compatibility path.  That means that
        if you misuse them today, they probably won't cause a problem,
        although they may someday later.  So, please be very careful
        only to use the DrawInfo structure between calls to
        @{"GetScreenDrawInfo()" LINK "GetScreenDrawInfo"} and @{"FreeScreenDrawInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 506}(), and be sure
        that you don't forget @{"FreeScreenDrawInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 506}().@{b}

   BUGS@{ub}@{b}

   SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"GetScreenDrawInfo()" LINK "GetScreenDrawInfo"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FreeSysRequest" "intuition.library/FreeSysRequest()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
        @{"FreeSysRequest" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 259} -- Free resources gotten by a call to @{"BuildSysRequest()" LINK "BuildSysRequest"}.@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        @{"FreeSysRequest" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 259}( Window )
                        A0

        @{"VOID" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 24} @{"FreeSysRequest" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 259}( @{"struct Window" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 909} * );@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
        This routine frees up all memory allocated by a successful call to
        the @{"BuildSysRequest()" LINK "BuildSysRequest"} procedure.  If @{"BuildSysRequest()" LINK "BuildSysRequest"} returned a
        pointer to a window, then you are able to wait on the message port
        of that window to detect an event which satisfies the requester.
        When you want to remove the requester, you call this procedure.  It
        ends the requester and deallocates any memory used in the creation
        of the requester.  It also closes the special window that was opened
        for your system requester.

        For V36: It's OK if you pass a @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101} or a @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95} (1) value to
        this function.  Also, this function properly disposes of
        requesters gotten using @{"BuildEasyRequestArgs()" LINK "BuildEasyRequestArgs"}.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
        Window = value of the window pointer returned by a successful call to
           the @{"BuildSysRequest()" LINK "BuildSysRequest"} procedure@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
        None@{b}

    BUGS@{ub}@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"BuildSysRequest()" LINK "BuildSysRequest"}, @{"AutoRequest()" LINK "AutoRequest"}, @{"CloseWindow()" LINK "CloseWindow"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "GadgetMouse" "intuition.library/GadgetMouse()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
        @{"GadgetMouse" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 387} -- Calculate gadget-relative mouse position. (V36)@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        @{"GadgetMouse" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 387}( Gadget, GInfo, MousePoint )
                     A0      A1     A2

        @{"VOID" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 24} @{"GadgetMouse" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 387}( @{"struct GadgetInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/cghooks.h/File" 25} *, @{"WORD" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 54} * );@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
        Determines the current location of the mouse pointer relative
        to the upper-left corner of a custom gadget.  Typically used
        only in the @{"GM_HANDLEINPUT" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 308} and @{"GM_GOACTIVE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 305} custom gadget hook
        routines.

        NEWS FLASH!!: These two hook routines are now passed the mouse
        coordinates, so this function has no known usefulness.

        We recommend that you don't call it.

        Note that this function calculates the mouse position taking
        "gadget relativity" (@{"GFLG_RELRIGHT" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 311}, @{"GFLG_RELBOTTOM" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 310}) into
        consideration.  If your custom gadget intends to ignore these
        properties, then you should either enjoin or inhibit your users
        from setting those bits, since Intuition won't ask if you respect
        them.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
        GInfo = A pointer to a GadgetInfo structure as passed to the
                custom gadget hook routine.
        MousePoint = address of two WORDS, or a pointer to a structure of
                type Point.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
        Returns nothing.  Fills in the two words pointed to by
        MousePoint with the gadget-relative mouse position.@{b}

    BUGS@{ub}
        Useless, since equivalent information is now passed to every
        function that might have a use for this.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "GetAttr" "intuition.library/GetAttr()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
        @{"GetAttr" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 477} -- Inquire the value of some attribute of an object. (V36)@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        attr = @{"GetAttr" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 477}( AttrID, Object, StoragePtr )
        D0              D0      A0      A1

        @{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52} @{"GetAttr" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 477}( @{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52}, @{"APTR" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 49}, @{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52} * );@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
        Inquires from the specified object the value of the specified attribute.

        You always pass the address of a long variable, which will
        receive the same value that would be passed to @{"SetAttrs()" LINK "SetAttrsA"} in
        the ti_Data portion of a TagItem element.  See the documentation
        for the class for exceptions to this general rule.

        Not all attributes will respond to this function.  Those that
        will are documented on a class-by-class basis.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
        AttrID = the attribute tag ID understood by the object's class
        Object = abstract pointer to the boopsi object you are interested in
        StoragePtr = pointer to appropriate storage for the answer@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
        Returns @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98} (0) if the inquiries of attribute are not provided
        by the object's class.@{b}

    NOTES@{ub}
        This function invokes the @{"OM_GET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 66} method of the object.@{b}

    BUGS@{ub}@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"NewObject()" LINK "NewObject"}, @{"DisposeObject()" LINK "DisposeObject"}, @{"SetAttrs()" LINK "SetAttrsA"}, @{"MakeClass()" LINK "MakeClass"},
        Document "Basic @{"Object" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 19}-Oriented Programming @{"System" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/dos/SystemTagList"} for @{"Intuition" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/intuition.h/File" 33}"
        and the "boopsi @{"Class" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classes.h/File" 36} Reference" document.

